The following is a very simple prototype of what you might be trying to achieve. We'll use HTML, CSS, and JavaScript. For the "sticky" functionality, we'll add a bit of resistance to the slider using JavaScript by only allowing it to increment in small amounts at a time. To make the task non-trivial we will make it so that it asymptotically approaches +-5.

The HTML:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <style>
        .slider {
            width: 100%;
            height: 15px;
            border-radius: 5px;
            background: #d3d3d3;
            outline: none;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <input type="range" min="0" max="10000" value="5000" class="slider" id="myRange">
    <p>Value: <span id="demo"></span></p>

    <script src="script.js"></script>
</body>
</html>
```

And the JavaScript (in "script.js"):

```javascript
let slider = document.getElementById("myRange");
let output = document.getElementById("demo");
let realVal = 0;
output.innerHTML = realVal;

slider.oninput = function() {
  let inputVal = (this.value - 5000) / 10000; // Normalize to range [-0.5, 0.5]

  // Apply the arctan function to create asymptotic behavior, then scale to desired range
  realVal = Math.atan(inputVal) * 2 / Math.PI; // arctan range is (-pi/2, pi/2), so this scales to (-1, 1)
  realVal *= 5; // Now scale to (-5, 5)

  output.innerHTML = realVal.toFixed(10); // Limiting to 10 decimal places for simplicity
}
```

The JavaScript uses the atan function to achieve the asymptotic behavior you asked for. Since atan asymptotically approaches pi/2 and -pi/2 as its input goes to infinity and -infinity, we divide by pi/2 to bring it to the range (-1, 1). Then we scale by 5 to bring it to the range (-5, 5).

The number is then displayed with 10 decimal places. If you want more or fewer decimal places, you can adjust the argument to the `toFixed()` function.

Note: This is a very basic example and may not perfectly suit your needs. For example, it doesn't implement a "pulling" interaction where the user has to keep dragging or clicking to increase the rating. Adding such an interaction would require significantly more complex JavaScript and probably a library to handle the complex interaction. If you're planning to use this in a production environment, you should definitely consider making it more robust and user-friendly.

Sure, we can modify the Javascript code to make it easier to move in the 0 to 1 range, and then start getting harder. We'll use a power function to get the exponential difficulty. The larger the exponent, the harder it is to increase the value. And I'll put it all in one HTML file for you:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <style>
        .slider {
            width: 100%;
            height: 15px;
            border-radius: 5px;
            background: #d3d3d3;
            outline: none;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <input type="range" min="0" max="10000" value="5000" class="slider" id="myRange">
    <p>Value: <span id="demo"></span></p>

    <script>
        let slider = document.getElementById("myRange");
        let output = document.getElementById("demo");
        let realVal = 0;
        output.innerHTML = realVal;

        slider.oninput = function() {
          let inputVal = (this.value - 5000) / 5000; // Normalize to range [-1, 1]

          if (inputVal >= 0) {
            // If the value is positive, apply the power function
            realVal = Math.pow(inputVal, 3) * 5; 
          } else {
            // If the value is negative, we also apply the power function but keep the sign
            realVal = -Math.pow(Math.abs(inputVal), 3) * 5;
          }
          output.innerHTML = realVal.toFixed(10); // Limiting to 10 decimal places for simplicity
        }
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

This will give you a slider that starts at 0, and as you move the slider, the number will increase but will get increasingly harder to increase as you get closer to 5. It works the same for negative numbers.

I apologize for the confusion. It's a bit tricky to directly manipulate the slider's behavior in a way that it provides resistance to dragging. Here's a workaround solution which creates an illusion of resistance by modifying the slider's value based on a logarithmic scale when moving towards the extremes:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <style>
        .slider {
            width: 100%;
            height: 15px;
            border-radius: 5px;
            background: #d3d3d3;
            outline: none;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <input type="range" min="0" max="1000" value="500" class="slider" id="myRange">
    <p>Value: <span id="demo"></span></p>

    <script>
        let slider = document.getElementById("myRange");
        let output = document.getElementById("demo");
        let realVal = 0;
        output.innerHTML = realVal;

        slider.oninput = function() {
            let inputVal = (this.value - 500) / 500; // Normalize to range [-1, 1]

            // Apply the function f(x) = (log2(2 + x) - 1), this creates a smoother effect from -1 to 1
            realVal = ((Math.log2(2 + Math.abs(inputVal)) - 1) * Math.sign(inputVal) * 5).toFixed(10); 

            // Update the output value
            output.innerHTML = realVal;

            // Update the slider's value based on the realVal, creating a "sticky" effect
            slider.value = (realVal / 5 * 500 + 500);
        }
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

This provides a sort of "resistance" by making the slider move more slowly as it approaches 5 or -5. The logarithmic function is used to scale the values more in the middle range and less in the extreme ranges, simulating a "resistance".

However, note that this is a rough approximation and does not offer true resistance in the sense of making it physically harder for the user to move the slider. It's a limitation of the range input type. For a more sophisticated solution, you may need to use a JavaScript UI library that offers more customizable slider inputs.

In that case, we would need to keep track of the last value and make the changes relative to that, instead of relative to the center. Here is an updated version of the code:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <style>
        .slider {
            width: 100%;
            height: 25px;
            border-radius: 5px;
            background: #d3d3d3;
            outline: none;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <input type="range" min="0" max="1000" value="500" class="slider" id="myRange">
    <p>Value: <span id="demo"></span></p>

    <script>
        let slider = document.getElementById("myRange");
        let output = document.getElementById("demo");
        let realVal = 0;
        let prevVal = 0;
        let sliderVal = 500;
        output.innerHTML = realVal;

        slider.oninput = function() {
            let inputVal = (this.value - 500) / 500; // Normalize to range [-1, 1]

            // Apply the function f(x) = (log2(2 + x) - 1), this creates a smoother effect from -1 to 1
            realVal = prevVal + (Math.log2(2 + Math.abs(inputVal)) - 1) * Math.sign(inputVal) * 5;

            if(realVal > 5){
                realVal = 5;
            }else if(realVal < -5){
                realVal = -5;
            }

            // Update the output value
            output.innerHTML = realVal.toFixed(10);

            // Update the slider's value based on the realVal, creating a "sticky" effect
            sliderVal += (this.value - sliderVal) / 5;
            this.value = sliderVal;

            prevVal = realVal;
        }
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

Now the changes are made relative to the previous value, which should give the behavior you're looking for. Each time you start dragging, it will start the logarithmic decay fresh from the current value. This means that if you stop dragging and then start again, the slider won't jump, but will start smoothly from where it left off. The maximum and minimum values have been limited to 5 and -5 respectively. Please try this updated code.

I apologize for the misunderstanding, the asymptotic "sticky" effect is challenging to implement. As it stands, HTML sliders do not inherently support this kind of feature. To develop this you would need to implement a custom slider element, probably involving SVGs and more advanced JavaScript. 

This would be more advanced than most basic examples and would involve capturing the user's mouse movements or touch movements and adjusting the slider position based on those movements and the current slider value.

Here's a basic JavaScript custom slider that has a sticky feel by implementing a delay on the slide movement:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <style>
        .container {
            width: 80%;
            margin: auto;
            position: relative;
            height: 10px;
            background-color: #d3d3d3;
            border-radius: 5px;
        }

        .slider {
            position: absolute;
            height: 20px;
            width: 20px;
            background-color: #4CAF50;
            border-radius: 50%;
            left: 50%;
            top: 50%;
            transform: translate(-50%, -50%);
        }

        #display {
            margin-top: 20px;
            text-align: center;
            font-size: 2em;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <div class="container" id="container">
        <div class="slider" id="slider"></div>
    </div>

    <div id="display">
        0.0000000000
    </div>

    <script>
        const slider = document.getElementById('slider');
        const container = document.getElementById('container');
        const display = document.getElementById('display');
        let sliderPos = 0;
        let mouseDown = false;
        let startX, endX;

        const updatePosition = () => {
            const newPos = Math.min(Math.max(sliderPos, 0), container.offsetWidth - slider.offsetWidth);
            slider.style.left = `${newPos}px`;
            const val = ((newPos - container.offsetWidth / 2) / container.offsetWidth * 10).toFixed(10);
            display.textContent = val;
        }

        slider.addEventListener('mousedown', (event) => {
            mouseDown = true;
            startX = event.clientX;
        });

        document.addEventListener('mouseup', () => {
            mouseDown = false;
        });

        document.addEventListener('mousemove', (event) => {
            if (mouseDown) {
                endX = event.clientX;
                const diff = (endX - startX);
                sliderPos += diff / 20; // Change the division factor to increase/decrease resistance
                updatePosition();
                startX = endX;
            }
        });

        // Initial position set
        sliderPos = container.offsetWidth / 2;
        updatePosition();
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

This slider has a "sticky" feel because it adds a delay to the slide movement. By dividing the difference between the starting and ending mouse positions (`diff / 20`), you can increase or decrease the resistance of the slider. The lower the division factor, the less resistance there will be, and the higher the division factor, the more resistance there will be.

However, keep in mind that this is still quite basic and doesn't exactly replicate an asymptotic function behavior. It simply slows down the slider movement to create a "resistant" feel. For a true asymptotic effect, a more complex mathematical approach would need to be implemented. The code becomes much more complex and might require using a dedicated UI library.

Here's how you might modify the previous script to make it less sticky in the middle and more sticky at the ends. This version applies a squaring operation to the fraction of the total distance the slider has moved, which makes the resistance grow more quickly as you approach the ends:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <style>
        .container {
            width: 80%;
            margin: auto;
            position: relative;
            height: 10px;
            background-color: #d3d3d3;
            border-radius: 5px;
        }

        .slider {
            position: absolute;
            height: 20px;
            width: 20px;
            background-color: #4CAF50;
            border-radius: 50%;
            left: 50%;
            top: 50%;
            transform: translate(-50%, -50%);
        }

        #display {
            margin-top: 20px;
            text-align: center;
            font-size: 2em;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <div class="container" id="container">
        <div class="slider" id="slider"></div>
    </div>

    <div id="display">
        0.0000000000
    </div>

    <script>
        const slider = document.getElementById('slider');
        const container = document.getElementById('container');
        const display = document.getElementById('display');
        let sliderPos = 0;
        let mouseDown = false;
        let startX, endX;

        const updatePosition = () => {
            const newPos = Math.min(Math.max(sliderPos, 0), container.offsetWidth - slider.offsetWidth);
            slider.style.left = `${newPos}px`;
            const val = ((newPos - container.offsetWidth / 2) / container.offsetWidth * 10).toFixed(10);
            display.textContent = val;
        }

        slider.addEventListener('mousedown', (event) => {
            mouseDown = true;
            startX = event.clientX;
        });

        document.addEventListener('mouseup', () => {
            mouseDown = false;
        });

        document.addEventListener('mousemove', (event) => {
            if (mouseDown) {
                endX = event.clientX;
                let diff = (endX - startX);
                const centerFraction = 2 * Math.abs(sliderPos / container.offsetWidth - 0.5);
                diff /= 10 * (centerFraction * centerFraction) + 1; // Modify the resistance factor here
                sliderPos += diff;
                updatePosition();
                startX = endX;
            }
        });

        // Initial position set
        sliderPos = container.offsetWidth / 2;
        updatePosition();
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

This creates a more "natural" feel, where the slider moves more easily in the middle and is more resistant towards the ends. The resistance factor is defined by the line `diff /= 10 * (centerFraction * centerFraction) + 1;` and can be adjusted as needed. The 10 is the maximum resistance at the end, and the +1 ensures there's always some minimum level of resistance. Feel free to adjust these values to better suit your needs.

